UPDATE:  I’ve been back a few times since my first review when the first opened and the quality of the food has improved.  The breakfast options are great and the coffee is good now:)  ORIGINAL REVIEW:I had heard great things about this place from Israeli friends and was excited to try it.  Overall I was underwhelmed.  The latte was good, mild, better then Starbucks not as good as Cafe Nero.  I ordered the Sharshuka with Halumi (a fried cheese that I love!).  It came with a tiny side salad that was iceberg with tomatoes and onion.  The tahini dressing was good.  I asked for the gluten free bread and got a microwaved Uddi’s role still in its plastic package. The presentation was a bit like airline food.  The Sharshuka was a big disappointment.  Perhaps because I’m used to the Tatte version right across the street.  It was smaller, less flavorful, the eggs were over cooked and the Halumi was massively inferior.  The atmosphere was nice but corporate and the prices were high. Realistically if I had gone to Tatte I would have received more food and better food for the same (also high) price.  The only thing Tatte doesn’t have is the gluten free bread, but the Sharshuka is so much better I don’t mind just skipping the bread.  Will I be back?  Probably yes.  The space would be good to accommodate a group of three or four (hard to find a table for that many across the street because it’s aleays packed.) And they have a broad menu where I’m sure anyone could find something they liked.   It’s kind of like a foreign Panera.  Not bad but nothing to write home about.

It’s really upsetting when everyone speaks so highly of a place that is vegan-friendly, and they just don’t deliver on that hype. On their website, there’s no mention of vegan desserts on their dedicated vegan menu, yet everyone said they have vegan rozalach; they never emailed back confirming if it is or not. So months later, we stopped by, and there’s wannabe Influencers taking photos without masks on outside and inside, and then a cashier who confirmed the Nutella and Lotus flavors are both vegan. We paid, then a friend mentioned the Nutella flavor has dairy (or course!) and we looked it up, confirmed on our own that Nutella definitely isn’t vegan, and had to request a refund. They claimed they couldn’t refund the amount right away and couldn’t give a receipt as proof of their intention to issue a refund. Days later and we are still waiting.  I assume this is an aberration because there’s endless five-star ratings and so many people posting about the vegan rozalach to social media. But this experience was so frustrating and hopefully a different location will provide a much smoother experience.

I ordered DoorDash. Chicken Shawarma Pure Belgian Hot Chocolate Chicken Shawarma sandwich Nutella Rosalach Mediterranean Energy Shake (PB) Salmon Benedict  Let's start at the top...  The Chicken Shawarma wasn't seasoned, it felt like they carved up a chicken, and put it into a bowl with flavorless rice.  The Hot Chocolate was in a kids cup, and didn't include whip cream as I asked. It also had enough air in it that it could possibly be classified as a Lays chip bag.  The Chicken Shawarma sandwich was dry, you can tell it's poorly made if the only thing I can taste in it, is cucumbers. Cucumbers are 95% water, if anyone wanted to know that random fact.  Nutella Rosalach was the only good thing out of this entire order, and half of this product isn't even made by the Cafe.  Mediterranean Energy Shake, felt like I was eating a frozen yogurt. A shake is not suppose to be so thick you can throw them against the wall, and not lose any of the contents.  And lastly the Salmon Benedict. I nearly vomited eating this. You're not suppose to base the produce in salt to try to cheese a freshly picked, salt water ocean taste, which is exactly what you did. Perhaps consider changing the menu item to "Salt Benedict, with added Salmon". I ended up throwing it away.  Look at all my reviews. I have never ever done a negative review of a restaurant. But, this mockery of the culinary arts is not only some of the worst food I've eaten, they steal your kidney to give it to you. The 2 cups of hot chocolate that I got was $7. Seven dollars. What the hell. Save yourself the money, because all this restaurant does is thrive on vanity, not actual skill. It's actually impressively bad.

I used a Nift certificate  to get take-out lunch for my wife and me. We got a falafel hummus bowl (which comes with two pitas) and a chicken shawarma entree (which comes with couscous and a salad). Overall, the experience was excellent. From the time I walked in and placed my order to leaving with it was only 10 minutes and the Nift certificate was handled easily.  The falafel was delicious - perfectly cooked and flavorful and the hummus was wonderfully creamy with just the right amount of tahini. It was WAY better than any store-bought hummus I've ever had. The pitas were small in diameter but thick, flavorful, and chewy, perfect for dipping into the hummus. The shawarma was also excellent and, when I asked if it was spicy (it was not) I was offered a small side cup of harissa which added just the right amount of heat. And the couscous was the best I've ever had - flavored with sauteed onion and spices. Having never been here, I was expecting a usual green salad but the herb salad is mostly parsley with some mint leaves, a few tomatoes, and a bit of red onion. Next time I come, I'll see if a more conventional salad could be substituted.  The service was friendly and helpful and, if my wife had been with me, we would probably have eaten on the patio. BTW, plenty of metered parking is right next to the Chestnut Hilll Avenue location.  My only nitpick is that the pricing seems to be the same for lunch or dinner and the amount of the main course (the shawarma and falafel (four smallish balls)) could be upped a bit at the price or the lunchtime pricing could be reduced a bit. But, I guess it's Brookline so that might explain it. Overall, though, for us, this was a find and we'll certainly be back.

She was very loud and her voice caught my attention.  I can understand disciplining an employee, but there is nothing that she could have done to have deserved such treatment. Pretty good. Pricey. Landwer breakfast was hit and miss. The labneh was fantastic, the Greek yogurt was good, feta very salty. But the tuna salad was not too appetizing (and I love tuna), and the guacamole was too thin. Needed more body, chunks of avo. The jam was disappointing. However I highly recommend the fried saganaki sticks - delicious! Unfortunately they came with a micro side of marinara for dipping, which was far from enough to last for all the sticks. I asked for another tiny side of marinara. It took ages to come and by the time it did, the sticks we're almost gone and had cooled too much. And when the bill came, I was surprised to see they had charged extra for it, that tiny little pot of marinara dipping sauce. Water was another issue. The waitress stopped by to ask how our food was but never came by to refill our water glasses. I was desperately thirsty and it took the entire meal before we were able to get her to finally bring us water. She was nice and helped me choose between dishes. But please come by a few times with water!  Next time I will try the shakshuka, and will definitely reorder the saganaki sticks.

Landwer Coffee was established by Moshe Landwer in 1919 in Berlin, Germany. The family operated a small coffee bar and a coffee roasting facility. In 1933, when the Nazis came to power in Germany, the family decided to immigrate to Tel Aviv. Immediately after their arrival, the Landwer family opened their first coffee roasting facility in Allenby Street, making it the first coffee roaster company in the country. Later, when the business expanded, the family moved the coffee bar to 121 Allenby Street.
